    "#### Spliting the column car details to Kilometers_driven, Fuel_Type, Transmission and Owner_Type"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "06df4e82",

    "id": "06df4e82"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "df5[['Kilometers_Driven','Fuel_Type','Transmission','Owner_Type']]=df5.CarDetail.apply(lambda x: pd.Series(str(x).split('•')))"
   ]

    "#function to split dataset int training and test\n",
    "def trainingData(df2,n):\n",
    "    X = df2.iloc[:,n]\n",
    "    y = df2.iloc[:,-1:].values.T\n",
    "    y=y[0]\n",
    "    X_train,X_test,y_train,y_test=train_test_split(X,y,train_size=0.9,test_size=0.1,random_state=0)\n",
    "    return (X_train,X_test,y_train,y_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "X_train,X_test,y_train,y_test=trainingData(df2,list(range(len(list(df2.columns))-1)))"
   ]

   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "4d778b7e",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "4d778b7e"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "#some of models will predict neg values so this function will remove that values\n",
    "def remove_neg(y_test,y_pred):\n",
    "    ind=[index for index in range(len(y_pred)) if(y_pred[index]>0)]\n",
    "    y_pred=y_pred[ind]\n",
    "    y_test=y_test[ind]\n",
    "    y_pred[y_pred<0]\n",
    "    return (y_test,y_pred)\n",
    "\n",
    "#function for evaluation of model\n",
    "def result(y_test,y_pred):\n",
    "    r=[]\n",
    "    r.append(mean_squared_log_error(y_test, y_pred))\n",
    "    r.append(np.sqrt(r[0]))\n",
    "    r.append(r2_score(y_test,y_pred))\n",
    "    r.append(round(r2_score(y_test,y_pred)*100,4))\n",
    "    return (r)\n",
    "\n",
    "#dataframe that store the performance of each model\n",
    "accu=pd.DataFrame(index=['MSLE', 'Root MSLE', 'R2 Score','Accuracy(%)']) "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d0e42c9d",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "d0e42c9d"
   },
   "source": [
    "##  Linear Regression"
   ]
  },
  {

   "source": [
    "#The below code is fitting a linear regression model to the training data, and then using that model to make predictions on the test data. The predicted values can then be compared to the true values in y_test to evaluate the performance of the model."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",

   "metadata": {
    "id": "50bc46b2"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "#fitting model\n",
    "LR=LinearRegression()\n",
    "LR.fit(X_train,y_train)\n",
    "y_pred=LR.predict(X_test)"
   ]
  },

    "#calculating error/accuracy\n",

    "print('Coefficients: \\n', LR.coef_)\n",

    "## Ridge Regression"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2YUgNFIe3EdQ",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "2YUgNFIe3EdQ"
   },
   "source": [
    "#Ridge regression can help address this issue by introducing a regularization term that penalizes large coefficients in the regression equation, thereby reducing the complexity of the model and helping to prevent overfitting."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "rEcs5zoc3Nhz",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "rEcs5zoc3Nhz"
   },
   "source": [
    "The below code is useful for selecting the best value of alpha for ridge regression, which can improve the model's ability to generalize to new data by preventing overfitting."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "cd820834",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "cd820834",
    "outputId": "f653749d-6abb-4dcd-ede8-8f61d4a937c2"
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x432 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "<AxesSubplot:title={'center':'RidgeCV Alpha Error'}, xlabel='alpha', ylabel='error (or score)'>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 726,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "#predicting value of alpha\n",
    "\n",
    "alphas = 10**np.linspace(10,-2,400)\n",
    "model = RidgeCV(alphas=alphas)\n",
    "visualizer = AlphaSelection(model)\n",
    "visualizer.fit(X_train,y_train)\n",
    "visualizer.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "Aa6I3toK3Tcr",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "Aa6I3toK3Tcr"
   },
   "source": [
    "finding the coefficients of the model that minimize the sum of squared errors between the predicted values and the actual values in the training data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",

   "source": [

    "RR.fit(X_train,y_train)\n",
    "y_pred=RR.predict(X_test)"
   ]

   "source": [
    "## KNN"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2PlWB0x04JgC",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "2PlWB0x04JgC"
   },
   "source": [
    "In KNN, given a new observation, the algorithm finds the k closest (i.e., \"nearest\") observations in the training set based on some similarity metric (e.g., Euclidean distance). For classification tasks, the output class is determined by the majority class among the k nearest neighbors. For regression tasks, the output is the average of the k nearest neighbor's values."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "7a7f4173",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "7a7f4173",
    "outputId": "f33a271d-2dcf-479b-f655-9f4ec3592f39"
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "K = 1  , Root MSLE = 0.569964011086684\n",
      "K = 2  , Root MSLE = 0.5138066313892785\n",
      "K = 3  , Root MSLE = 0.5001185432177171\n",
      "K = 4  , Root MSLE = 0.49163957706858447\n",
      "K = 5  , Root MSLE = 0.49746951245126897\n",
      "K = 6  , Root MSLE = 0.5026863489809129\n",
      "K = 7  , Root MSLE = 0.5044889597698925\n",
      "K = 8  , Root MSLE = 0.508152393093826\n",
      "K = 9  , Root MSLE = 0.5091277212253594\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "#estimating MSLE for k=1-9\n",
    "R_MSLE=[]\n",
    "for i in range(1,10):\n",
    "    KNN=KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=i)\n",
    "    KNN.fit(X_train,y_train)\n",
    "    y_pred=KNN.predict(X_test)\n",
    "    error=np.sqrt(mean_squared_log_error(y_test, y_pred))\n",
    "    R_MSLE.append(error)\n",
    "    print(\"K =\",i,\" , Root MSLE =\",error)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "e240ec38",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "e240ec38",
    "outputId": "116f0ef0-8c12-45ad-8078-3117f0167cad"
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 576x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "#plotting error\n",
    "\n",
    "curve = pd.DataFrame(R_MSLE) #elbow curve \n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(8,4))\n",
    "plt.xticks(list(range(1,10)), list(range(1,10)), rotation='horizontal')\n",
    "plt.plot(list(range(1,10)),R_MSLE)\n",
    "plt.xlabel('K')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('MSLE')\n",
    "plt.title('Error Plot for Each K')\n",
    "plt.savefig('KNN-Error-Plot.jpg')\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },

    "## Random Forest"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "Dtsm7M8S5Xz8",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "Dtsm7M8S5Xz8"
   },
   "source": [
    "To make a prediction for a new input, the Random Forest algorithm passes it through each of the decision trees and takes the majority vote of their individual predictions, resulting in a final prediction for the input. The randomness in the selection of the subsets of data and features helps to reduce overfitting and improve the accuracy and generalization of the model."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "c829f3c3",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "c829f3c3"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "RFR = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=180,random_state=0, min_samples_leaf=1, max_features=0.5, n_jobs=-1, oob_score=True)\n",
    "RFR.fit(X_train,y_train)\n",
    "y_pred = RFR.predict(X_test)"
   ]
  },

    "## Bagging  Regressor"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "FrWRbE2z6tP7",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "FrWRbE2z6tP7"
   },
   "source": [
    "In the context of used car price prediction, Bagging Regressor can be trained on a dataset containing information about different cars such as their make, model, year, mileage, condition, and other relevant features. The algorithm can then be used to predict the selling price of a used car based on these features.\n",
    "\n",
    "The Bagging Regressor can handle nonlinear relationships between the features and the target variable, and can also deal with missing data and outliers. It can be tuned to improve the accuracy of the model, and can be combined with other techniques such as feature engineering and hyperparameter optimization to further improve the performance."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "dd6079e9",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "dd6079e9"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "#model implementation\n",
    "baggReg=BaggingRegressor(base_estimator=DecisionTreeRegressor(max_depth=20),n_estimators=50, random_state=1,\n",
    "                         max_samples=1.0, max_features=1.0, bootstrap=False, \n",
    "                         bootstrap_features=False, oob_score=False, warm_start=False, n_jobs=-1, verbose=0)\n",
    "baggReg.fit(X_train,y_train)\n",
    "y_pred=baggReg.predict(X_test)"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9da4b99b",
   "metadata": {

   },
   "source": [
    "## Adaboost"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "H0y4rmoN7nMj",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "H0y4rmoN7nMj"
   },
   "source": [
    "Adaboost works by iteratively training weak learners on different subsets of the training data and adjusting the weights of the training instances to focus on the misclassified instances in each iteration. In each iteration, the algorithm gives more weight to the instances that were misclassified in the previous iteration, and less weight to the instances that were correctly classified. This helps the algorithm to focus on the hard-to-predict instances, and improves the overall accuracy of the model."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "da5cbce4",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "da5cbce4"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "#model implementation\n",
    "ABR = AdaBoostRegressor(\n",
    "    DecisionTreeRegressor(max_depth=24),\n",
    "    n_estimators=200,learning_rate=0.6\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "ABR.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
    "y_pred = ABR.predict(X_test)"
   ]
  },
  {

      "R2 Score : 0.8532742892224173 or 85.3274%\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "#model evaluation\n",
    "r7_ab=result(y_test,y_pred)\n",
    "print(\"MSLE : {}\".format(r7_ab[0]))\n",
    "print(\"Root MSLE : {}\".format(r7_ab[1]))\n",
    "print(\"R2 Score : {} or {}%\".format(r7_ab[2],r7_ab[3]))"

    "XGBoost (Extreme Gradient Boosting) is a powerful machine learning algorithm that has been used with great success for predicting the price of a used car. XGBoost is an ensemble method that combines multiple decision trees, with each tree built iteratively to minimize the loss function."
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,

    "make = input(\"Enter make of the car: \")\n",
    "model_name = input(\"Enter model of the car: \")\n",
    "year = int(input(\"Enter year of the car: \"))\n",
    "mileage = float(input(\"Enter mileage of the car (Km/L): \"))\n",
    "engine_cc = int(input(\"Enter engine CC of the car: \"))\n",

    "fuel_type = input(\"Enter fuel type of the car: \")\n",
    "transmission = input(\"Enter transmission type of the car: \")\n",
    "owner_type = input(\"Enter owner type of the car: \")\n",
    "kms=input(\"Enter the kilometers_driven by the car\")\n",
    "# Create a dataframe with the input values\n",
    "input_data = pd.DataFrame({'Location': [location],\n",
    "                          'Manufacturer': [make],\n",
    "                          'model': [model_name],\n",

  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "de81e7a9",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "de81e7a9",
    "outputId": "dacaf3ec-4557-4e6c-ac05-6e1356b739f5"
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "{'Location': LabelEncoder(), 'Manufacturer': LabelEncoder(), 'Fuel_Type': LabelEncoder(), 'Transmission': LabelEncoder(), 'Owner_Type': LabelEncoder()}\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "print(label_encoders)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "84f65104",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "84f65104",
    "outputId": "911d05f7-2c64-4bc6-a294-63f8a9174b2c"
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Predicted car price: Rs 6.70 Lakhs\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder\n",
    "def preprocess_and_predict_price(num_col, cat_cols, input_data, le, model):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Preprocesses input data and predicts car price using trained model.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Args:\n",
    "    - num_col (list): List of column names containing numerical features.\n",
    "    - cat_cols (list): List of column names containing categorical features.\n",
    "    - input_data (DataFrame): Input data containing both numerical and categorical features.\n",
    "    - label_encoder (LabelEncoder): Trained LabelEncoder object.\n",
    "    - model: Trained machine learning model.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Returns:\n",
    "    - predicted_price (float): Predicted car price.\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Preprocess numerical features\n",
    "    num_data = input_data[num_col]\n",
    "    # Preprocess categorical features\n",
    "    #cat_data = input_data[cat_cols].apply(lambda x: le.transform(x))\n",
    "    # Concatenate numerical and categorical features\n",
    "    num_data['age']=2023-num_data['Year']\n",
    "    cat_data = input_data[cat_cols]\n",
    "    cat_data = cat_data.apply(lambda x: label_encoders[x.name].transform(x))\n",
    "    cat_data = pd.DataFrame(cat_data, columns=cat_cols)\n",
    "    final_cols=['Manufacturer','age','Year','Location','Kilometers_Driven','Fuel_Type','Transmission','Owner_Type','Engine CC','Power','Seats','Mileage Km/L']\n",
    "    input_data_processed = pd.concat([cat_data,num_data], axis=1)\n",
    "    input_data_processed= input_data_processed[final_cols]\n",
    "    # Make predictions\n",
    "    predicted_price = model.predict(input_data_processed)\n",
    "    return predicted_price[0]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Call the preprocess_and_predict_price function to preprocess input data and predict car price\n",
    "predicted_price = preprocess_and_predict_price(num_col, cat_cols, input_data, label_encoders, xg_reg)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Print predicted car price\n",
    "print(\"Predicted car price: Rs\",\"%.2f\" %predicted_price,\"Lakhs\")\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
